Inclusion Criteria (All of the following MUST be YES
Patients presenting to the Foothills Medical Centre emergency department with:
Acute ischemic stroke deficits and are considered potential candidates for thrombolytic treatment (either IV or IA or a combination of both)

VarLabel: Symptom onset within 12 hours from time last seen normal if anterior circlation strokes and 24 hours from last seen normal if posterior circulation strokes and 24 hours from last seen normal if posterior circulation strokes (include wake up strokes if it satisfies criteria above).
Exclusion Criteria:   (All of the following MUST be NO)
Unable to have CT-angio performed due to known renal impairment, contrast allergy, agitation or some other reason
NCCT showing tumor, intracerebral hemorrhage, subdural hematoma or other space-occupying lesion
Deficits felt by the investigator to be definitively of non-vascular origin (e.g. migraine, hypoglycemia, seizure, obvious psychogenic cause of deficits etc.)
Serious co-morbid illness that would result in the patient being unlikely to survive three months

FBI-1. Apathy: Has s/he lost interest in friends or daily activities
FBI-2. Apontaneity: Does s/he start things on his/her own, or does s/he have to be asked?
FBI-3. Indifference, Emotional Flatness: Does s/he respond to occasions of joy or sadness as much as ever, or has s/he lost emotional responsiveness?
FBI-4. Inflexibility: Can s/he change his/her mind with reason or does s/he appear stubbor or rigid in thinking lately?
FBI-5. Concreteness: Does s/he interpret what is being said appropriately or does s/he choose only the concrete meanings of what is being said?
FBI-6. Personal Neglect: Does s/he take as much care of his/her personal hygiene and appearance as usual?
VarDescription: Is personal neglect present in patient

VarLabel: FBI-7. Disorganization: Can s/he plan and organize complex activity or is s/he easily distractible, impersistent, or unable to complete a job?
FBI-8. Inattention: Odes s/he pay attention to what is going on or does s/he seem to loose track or not follow at all?
FBI-9. Loss of Insight: Is s/he aware of any problems or changes, or does s/he seem unaware of them ro deny them when discussed?
VarDescription: Is loss of insight present in patient

VarLabel: FBI-10. Logopenia: Has s/he been talking clearly or has s/he been making errors in speech? Is there slurring or hesitation?
FBI-11. Verbal Apraxia: Has s/he been talking clearly or has s/he been making errors in speech? Is there slurring or hesitation?
VarDescription: Is verbal apraxia present in patient

VarLabel: FBI-12. Perseveration: Does s/he repeat or persevate actions or remarks?
FBI-13. Irritibility: Has s/he been irritable, short-tempered, or is s/he reacting to stress or frustration as s/he always had
FBI-14. Excessive Jocularity: Has s/he been making jokes excessivly or offensively or at the wrong time
VarDescription: Has excessive jocularity been present in patient

VarLabel: FBI-15. Poor Judgement: Has s/he been using good judgement in decisions or in driving, or has s/he acted irresponsibly, neglectfully or in poor judgment?
FBI-17. Impulsivity: Has s/he acted or spoken without thinking about consequences, or on the spur of the moment?
FBI-18. Restlessness: Has s/he shown aggression, or shouted at anyone or hurt them physically?
FBI-19. Aggression: Has s/he shown aggression, or shouted at anyone or hurt them physically?
FBI-Hyperporality: Has s/he been drinking more than usual, eating excessively anything in sight, or even putting objects in his/her mouth?
FBI-22. Utilization Behaviour: Does s/he seem to need to touch, feel, examine, or pick up objects within reach and sight
FBI-23. Incontinence: Does s/he have any problem using a hanf, and does it interfere with the other hand?
FBI-24. Alien Hand-Does s/he have any problem using a hand, and does it interfere with the other hand? (excluding arthritis, trauma, paralysis etc.)
